SIMPLE: duenna
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Duenna
<hw>Du*en"na</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Duennas</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp. <ets>due⟦ntil⟧a</ets>,
<ets>do⟦ntil⟧a</ets>, fr. L. <ets>domina</ets>. See
<er>Dame</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The chief lady in waiting on the
queen of Spain.</def> <rj><au>Brande.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An elderly lady holding a station between a
governess and companion, and appointed to have charge over the younger
ladies in a Spanish or a Portuguese family.</def> <rj><au>Brande &
C.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any old woman who is employed to guard a younger
one; a governess.</def> <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Duet</ent>⟦br⟧
